3:# Recipe 7.4: ED Visit Prediction (Python Example)
9:## Setup
26:## Config and Constants
35:# ─── Risk Tier Thresholds ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
36:# These thresholds determine which patients get outreach. They're not magic
37:# numbers: you calibrate them based on your care management team's capacity.
38:# If you can only call 200 patients per week, set HIGH_RISK_THRESHOLD so that
39:# roughly 200 patients land above it in each scoring run.
40:#
41:# The gap between medium and high matters operationally. High-risk patients
42:# get a nurse call within 48 hours. Medium-risk get a mailer and a pharmacy
43:# check-in. Low-risk get nothing (for now).
47:# Below 0.40: no intervention (standard care)
49:# ─── Feature Configuration ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
50:# These are the features we'll engineer from claims and clinical data.
51:# In production, you'd pull these from a feature store. Here we generate
52:# synthetic versions to demonstrate the pipeline shape.
71:# ─── Model Parameters ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
72:# Gradient boosted trees work well here because:
73:# 1. They handle mixed feature types (continuous + binary) without scaling
74:# 2. They capture non-linear interactions (age + CHF + lives alone)
75:# 3. They produce feature importance rankings for clinical explainability
76:# 4. They're robust to missing values (common in claims data)
87:# ─── Prediction Window ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
